<subSubSection id="04B6D9C7FFD0C918FF278C0383A871A2" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4C138A4CFFD0C918FF278C03832F74A2" blockId="21.[174,781,608,1720]" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF278C03805B7562" authorityName="SAULCY" authorityYear="1878" box="[174,312,608,632]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FF278C03805B7562" box="[174,312,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Typhlocyptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
previously included two valid species, the 
<typeStatus id="931734EEFFD0C918FF278CE381BF7582" box="[174,220,640,664]" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FEB98CE383547582" authority="SAULCY, 1878" authorityName="SAULCY" authorityYear="1878" box="[304,567,640,664]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pandellei">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FEB98CE380C57582" box="[304,422,640,664]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">T. pandellei</emphasis>
SAULCY, 1878
</taxonomicName>
(South Europe) and 
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF278CC3801875A2" authority="PACE, 1985" authorityName="PACE" authorityYear="1985" box="[174,379,672,696]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loebli">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FF278CC3819C75A2" box="[174,255,672,696]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">T. loebli</emphasis>
PACE, 1985
</taxonomicName>
(North 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FE5B8CC3836F75A2" box="[466,524,672,696]" name="India" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">India</collectingCountry>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="283DF7BDFFD0C918FDAA8CC2818575C2" author="SCHULKE, M. &amp; SMETANA, A." pageId="21" pageNumber="260" pagination="304 - 1134" refId="ref47786" refString="SCHULKE, M. &amp; SMETANA, A. 2015: Staphylinidae, pp. 304 - 1134. - In: LOBL, I. &amp; LOBL, D. (eds), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. New, updated Edition. Volume 2. Hydrophiloidea - Staphylinoidea. Revised and updated edition. - Leiden: Brill: xxvi + 1702 pp." type="book chapter" year="2015">SCHÜLKE &amp; SMETANA 2015</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF738CA3808875C2" authorityName="SAULCY" authorityYear="1878" box="[250,491,704,728]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pandellei">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FF738CA3808875C2" box="[250,491,704,728]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Typhlocyptus pandellei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two junior synonyms 
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF278C8380EB75E2" authority="REY, 1882" authorityName="REY" authorityYear="1882" box="[174,392,736,760]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atomus">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FF278C83807675ED" box="[174,277,736,759]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">T. atomus</emphasis>
REY, 1882
</taxonomicName>
(described from Southeast 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FD308C83826075E2" box="[697,771,736,760]" name="France" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">France</collectingCountry>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF6B8D6380927402" authority="MATCHA, 1916" authorityName="MATCHA" authorityYear="1916" box="[226,497,768,792]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="halleri">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FF6B8D63805C7402" box="[226,319,768,792]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">T. halleri</emphasis>
MATCHA, 1916
</taxonomicName>
(described from 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FD328D6381937422" name="Serbia" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Montenegro</collectingCountry>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="283DF7BDFFD0C918FE158D4283BF7422" author="SCHULKE, M. &amp; SMETANA, A." box="[412,732,800,828]" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" pagination="304 - 1134" refId="ref47786" refString="SCHULKE, M. &amp; SMETANA, A. 2015: Staphylinidae, pp. 304 - 1134. - In: LOBL, I. &amp; LOBL, D. (eds), Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera. New, updated Edition. Volume 2. Hydrophiloidea - Staphylinoidea. Revised and updated edition. - Leiden: Brill: xxvi + 1702 pp." type="book chapter" year="2015">SCHÜLKE &amp; SMETANA (2015)</bibRefCitation>
, the species is widespread from 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FE598D238379744D" box="[464,538,832,855]" name="France" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">France</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FDAC8D2383C77442" box="[549,676,832,856]" name="Switzerland" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FD558D2382687442" box="[732,779,832,856]" name="Italy" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Italy</collectingCountry>
across the Balkans (
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FE0C8D0380BB7462" box="[389,472,864,888]" name="Croatia" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Croatia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FE6C8D0383527462" box="[485,561,864,888]" name="Greece" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Greece</collectingCountry>
) eastwards to 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FD468D0381917482" name="Azerbaijan" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Azerbaijan</collectingCountry>
. It was recently reported from 
<collectingCountry id="34BBCADCFFD0C918FDDD8DE383B47482" box="[596,727,896,920]" name="Serbia" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Montenegro</collectingCountry>
and tentatively from Crete (
<bibRefCitation id="283DF7BDFFD0C918FE2A8DC3832274A2" author="ASSING, V." box="[419,577,928,952]" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" pagination="7 - 15" refId="ref47402" refString="ASSING, V. 2018 b: On the Staphylinidae of Crete III. The first records of endogean fauna (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Leptotyphlinae, Aleocharinae). - Linzer Biologische Beitrage 50 (1): 7 - 15. - https: // www. zobodat. at / pdf / LBB _ 0050 _ 1 _ 0007 - 0015. pdf." type="journal article" year="2018">ASSING 2018b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C138A4CFFD0C918FF278DA380B973A2" blockId="21.[174,781,608,1720]" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF278DA380FF74C2" authorityName="SAULCY" authorityYear="1878" box="[174,412,960,984]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pandellei">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FF278DA380FF74C2" box="[174,412,960,984]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Typhlocyptus pandellei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a minute beetle (length of forebody 
<quantity id="8B5427A9FFD0C918FF618D83800574ED" box="[232,358,992,1016]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" unit="mm" value="0.45" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.4">0.4–0.5 mm</quantity>
; b ody length 
<quantity id="8B5427A9FFD0C918FE788D83831374ED" box="[497,624,992,1016]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.9 mm</quantity>
, dep ending on how much the abdomen is extended). It is anophthalmous, apterous, and weakly pigmented and, based on personal observations, lives in a subterranean habitat. A winged morph is unknown. Against this background, both a wide distribution and its presence in 
<collectingRegion id="8E6844AEFFD0C918FE768AE3835A7382" box="[511,569,1152,1176]" country="Greece" name="Kriti" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Crete</collectingRegion>
would appear most remarkable and implausible.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C138A4CFFD0C918FF278AA383A871A2" blockId="21.[174,781,608,1720]" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FF278AA3806573C2" box="[174,262,1216,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Allotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">A major</taxonomicName>
problem for a taxonomic approach to this problem based on morphological characters is the uniformity not only of external, but also of the male sexual characters. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName id="8BACF1CFFFD0C918FE3A8B43835E7222" authorityName="SAULCY" authorityYear="1878" box="[435,573,1312,1336]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Typhlocyptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7ED8565EFFD0C918FE3A8B43835E7222" box="[435,573,1312,1336]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Typhlocyptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is of a unique and highly derived morphology: the minute, depigmented, and structurally simple ventral process and parameres are conspicuously separated from the basal capsule; both are connected only by a long transparent tube (
<figureCitation id="D49796C9FFD0C918FD0E8BC3826272A2" box="[647,769,1440,1464]" captionStart="Figs 57–70" captionStartId="9.[174,214,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[179,1413,262,1990]" captionTargetId="figure-49@9.[174,1421,255,1994]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 57–70: Typhlocyptus creticus (57–60), T. pandellei (61–62), Geomitopsis cretica (63–64), and Allotyphlus foedatus (65–70): aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (57–58, 61–64, 67–70); ventral process of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (59–60); male sternites VI–VIII (65); male sternite VIII (66). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755252" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755252/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Figs 57–58</figureCitation>
). In consequence, a dissection of a complete aedeagus is possible only in fresh and soft specimens. The basal portion of the aedeagus is of uniform shape in all the examined material. Slight differences, however, were found in the shape of the ventral process between populations from 
<collectingRegion id="8E6844AEFFD0C918FEAA8803803E7162" box="[291,349,1632,1656]" country="Greece" name="Kriti" pageId="21" pageNumber="260">Crete</collectingRegion>
and from the mainland. Whether or not the mainland populations all belong to the same species can be assessed only using a DNA-based approach.
</paragraph>
